Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 475 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @tomato{1}(diced). Trim, peel, and thinly slice half the @red onion{1/2}(sliced) 
(whole onion for 4 servings); mince a few slices until you have 1 TBSP (2 TBSP for 4). 
Quarter @lime{1}(quartered). Halve, deseed, and dice @long green pepper{1}(diced).

In a #small bowl{}, combine tomato, minced onion, a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp}, 
and a squeeze of lime juice. Season with @salt{1/2%tsp} and @black pepper{1/2%tsp}.

Open package of @chopped chicken breast{10%oz} and drain off any excess liquid.  
Heat a large drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add green pepper, 
sliced onion, salt, and pepper. Cook until veggies are softened, ~{4-6%minutes}. 
(TIP: Add a splash of water if veggies begin to brown too quickly.) Turn off heat. 
Transfer veggies to a #medium bowl{}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pan used for veggies over medium-high heat. Add chicken 
and season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until browned, 
~{3-5%minutes}.

Return veggies to pan. Stir in half the @Tex-Mex paste{1%unit}, half the 
@southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest of each later), and 
@water{1/4%cup}. Cook until everything is coated and chicken is cooked through, 
~{2-3%minutes} more. Turn off heat.

Place a small amount of filling on one half of each @flour tortillas{6}. Roll up 
tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create enchiladas. Place, seam sides down, 
in an #8-by-8-inch baking dish{} (9-by-13-inch dish for 4 servings) or #ovenproof pan{}.

In a second small bowl, combine @tomato paste{1}, remaining Tex-Mex paste, remaining 
Southwest Spice Blend, and @water{1/2%cup}.

Pour sauce over enchiladas. Sprinkle with @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}.

Bake on top rack until sauce is bubbly and cheese is melted, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Top enchiladas with pico de gallo. Divide between plates. Dollop with 
@sour cream{1 1/2%tablespoon} and serve with remaining lime wedges on the side.